Compulsory cycling lessons in schools 'would make for fitter, happier, safer children'
Cycling should be placed on the National Curriculum to combat the obesity crisis and improve levels of road safety, according to a powerful coalition of transport and health experts. By Gregg Morgan
6:00AM BST 24 Apr 2013
Follow Comments
Pupils from the age of five upwards should be given lessons in riding a bike and negotiating traffic amid fears too many children are failing to take up the “essential life skill” on a daily basis, it is claimed. In a letter to The Daily Telegraph, organisations including the AA, the Road Haulage Association, British Cycling and the UK Health Forum claim that cycling should have the same status in the physical education curriculum as swimming. The call is made a week after the Government closed a major consultation into a proposed overhaul of the lessons for five to 14-year-olds in England. Speaking outside Look Mum No Hands cycle café in central London, David Dansky, one of the letter's signatories, told the Telegraph that the compulsory training would not only give children the necessary skills to ride to school but would give parents more confidence to allow them in the first place. "Kids should cycle, not sit in the back of a people carrier," said the Association of Bikeability Schemes director. Related Articles
