Socialite accused of lying in court to win record settlement
When a judge ordered her former fiancé to pay her a record £27,000 a month in child support, Annabelle Bond no doubt celebrated in style.
Miss Bond was accused by her former boyfriend of moving from 'one millionaire lover to another to support her lavish lifestyle' Photo: PA	By Victoria Ward
7:12PM BST 25 Apr 2013
Follow The socialite daughter of former HSBC chairman Sir John Bond could not have predicted that she would subsequently become caught up in a bitter legal battle, accused of lying to the court about her financial means in order to “achieve a higher windfall”. Warren Lichtenstein, a US hedge fund manager and the father of her five-year-old daughter, has demanded substantial damages after claiming that Miss Bond conspired with her new boyfriend in order to win the largest child support settlement awarded in Hong Kong’s legal history. He has accused the 44-year-old of issuing the court with “misleading and inaccurate statements” in an attempt to “improve upon her already extraordinary life of leisure, luxury, privilege and modest fame”. In a lawsuit filed this week in New York, Mr Lichtenstein accused his “embittered former girlfriend” of falsely telling the court that £2.2 million given to her by her boyfriend, Andrew Cader, 54, was a loan that she had to repay. Lawyers for Miss Bond said the allegations made by Mr Lichtenstein in his US Complaint and referred to in this article are "utterly denied".
