Libyan may settle 'torture' case for £3
A Libyan politician suing the British Government after being kidnapped and tortured has offered to settle the case for £3, as long as he also receives an unreserved apology.
Mr Belhaj was an opponent of Col Gaddafi Photo: AP	By Telegraph Reporters
6:15AM GMT 04 Mar 2013
Follow Abdel Hakim Belhaj, leader of the Libyan Islamic Fighting Group, was held with his wife by American intelligence officers at Bangkok airport after an alleged tip-off by MI6.
The couple were then flown to Tripoli, where Mr Belhaj, who opposed the opposed Libyan dictator, Col Muammar Gaddafi, was tortured during his six years in jail. His wife, who was five months’ pregnant, was chained to a wall at a secret prison at the airport, it was reported. He launched legal action against the government, after secret documents found in Tripoli showed Sir Mark Allen, former head of counter-terrorism at MI6 had written to Musa Kusa, Col Gaddafi’s then intelligence chief, claiming credit for the tip-off. Last night it emerged that Mr Belhaj, a leading figure in the rebel forces before the dictator was killed,he has written to David Cameron saying he would settle his case for a “token compensation” of one pound each from the government, Jack Straw, the former Foreign Secretary and Sir Mark. Related Articles
French embassy in Tripoli hit by car bomb
23 Apr 2013
Christians in Libya being rounded up and beaten
13 Mar 2013
A good balance between security and liberty
04 Mar 2013
Libya elections: Muslim Brotherhood set to lead government
05 Jul 2012
