Redecorating ideas: out with the beige, in with the burnt orange At last, we're ditching neutral beige tones and opting for bold, bright shades of paint, says Caroline McGhie.
Image 1 of 2	Jewel-like: Stephen and Assia Webster's vivid Kent home is for sale through Stutt and Parker Image 1 of 2	Study in plum: 'Colour is important because it is one of the first things people notice when they visit a house' By Caroline McGhie
7:00AM GMT 28 Jan 2010
Comments
Stephen and Assia Webster habitually wrap themselves in jewels and colour. Why wouldn't they? He is the rock-and-roll jeweller to the stars, she is a Russian exotic. A man who creates for Kate Moss an articulated lobster made of brown diamonds and coral, and a woman who is completely comfortable in fuchsia fishnets, could do no other.
Enter the front door of their town house in Kent and you are enveloped in dark purple.
The sitting room then opens out into a rich Italian red, furnished with sofas and chairs in dark red, pepper and aubergine. The large cowhide on the floor is the kind of thing you find in ski lodges high in the Alps. Upstairs they have a bedroom in red and black, and a guest room which is more neutral. "It is a soft lime because we didn't want to shock our guests," says Assia. One child's room is lilac and red, another has a blue wall with white clouds dancing across it. But their decision to sell the six-bedroom Georgian house in Walmer raised questions about the decoration.
"We were asked by the estate agents to tone it down," says Assia. "But if someone really likes the house they can do what they like with it. And this certainly gives it more character. My husband absolutely loves colour, and this is like a jewellery casket filled with precious stones. It is a reflection of his work." Stephen's jewellery is loved by glitterati including Madonna, Johnny Depp and Cameron Diaz, and Victoria Beckham proudly sported the mosquito ring (white gold, white diamond wings, silver diamond tail) he had designed in aid of malaria prevention. The house is for sale through Strutt & Parker (01227 451123) at £475,000.
Stephen and Assia may be international glamour gipsies, but theirs is a dilemma we all face. Should we decorate before selling? If we do, then should we pursue the wild and exotic or go for the creams and whites that estate agents recommend? "If a house is a bit tired we always try to get people to redecorate the key rooms," says Charlie Willis of Strutt & Parker. "It is worth spending £5,000 to £6,000 because it makes a sale go through quickly and maxes the price." Related Articles
Bathrooms show that big is still beautiful
17 Feb 2010
Nina Campbell's guide to decorating with colour
05 Mar 2010
But does it really count for so much? "It makes it more saleable," he says. "And if a house doesn't sell quickly then it affects the price because buyers think they can get it for less. A spot of colour is good but neutral is best because it doesn't put people off. I sold a house owned by a woman who painted the side of the bath pink to go with the bathroom curtains. That had to go." In playing safe, however, estate agents are out of step with changing trends. Crown Paints says the big colour of the past decade was Chocolate Comtesse, a sort of mushroom soup colour hovering somewhere between mauve and brown. The company predicts that we will become bolder in the next 10 years, opting for stripes and blocks of different colours, and our taste will become hotter, leading us to choose "synthetic purples, burnt oranges and deep greys".
At the Paint & Paper Library, where paint expert David Oliver has perfected 240 colours, many of them based on historic houses and their needs, tastes are moving in the same direction. Top sellers include Sugared Violet, Rhubarb, Very Well Read (think crushed library) and Hot Earth. David is both imaginative and scientific in his approach. Half the colours are "architectural", which means they are arranged in tonal families with five in each so that you can paint the doors, windows, ceilings and walls, and know they will all go together.
"Colour is important because it is one of the first things people notice when they visit a house and it is what they remember when they have left it. We use it as a memory tool," he says. "And people are definitely going for more colour now. There is a huge move away from the taupe and white which all the television shows were advocating two years ago, thinking only of the property resale value. People now think that if they have to stay put they will have the colours they want. They will express their personalities." Are we getting off-white fatigue? "People have got tired of walking in and seeing a flat-screen television and a B & Q Italia sofa. They knew the price of everything and the value of nothing. Now they are rediscovering how to use furniture, art, how to upholster a bed base." What shall it be then? Blackcurrant Crush or Gazelle Grey?
Contrasts Dazzle with white: Chelsea town house in Manresa Road with four bedrooms at £4.5m through Strutt & Parker (020 7225 3866).
Titillate with colour: Marine Palms, Torquay, Devon, with two bedrooms, bay views and decorated with a "theatrical or mildly erotic theme", according to agents Fulfords (01392 660007), who are asking £499,950.
Reassure with country cosy: Bank House, Ascott, in the Cotswolds, with seven bedrooms, sitting rooms of primrose yellow and wisteria blue, at £1.1m through Strutt & Parker (01608 650502). DECADES IN COLOUR (Source: Crown Paints)
Sixties: psychedelia and bolds (influence: pop culture)
Seventies: pastels and sprigs (think Laura Ashley)
Eighties: neon, monochrome (power dressing)
Nineties: Mediterranean brights and neutrals (all that foreign travel)
Noughties: naturals and warms (the new eco awareness)
PAINT KNOW-HOW (Source: Paint and Paper Library)
1. Use everyday possessions as a starting point – a dress, jewellery or painting.
2. Colours that most attract you first will be the easiest to live with.
3. Light dramatically affects the way colours appear; look in daylight and under artificial light.
4. Paint the inside of a shoebox first.
5. Always work from actual samples of paint. Interiors and Shopping
